1) Classification tree model (3 points)

In this problem you are going to work with the OJ dataset from the ISLR package. This dataset records purchases of two types of orange juices and presents customer and product characteristics as features. The goal is to predict which of the juices is chosen in a given purchase situation. See ?ISLR::OJ?ISLR::OJ for a description of the variables.

Load the data:

data <- data.table(OJ)

a) Create a training data of 75% and keep 25% of the data as a test set.

Modify some variables. It is not really needed for tree based models, but I converted some numeric variables to factor variables:

data$StoreID <- as.factor(data$StoreID) #store ID variable
data$WeekofPurchase <- as.factor(data$WeekofPurchase) #week of purchaes
data$SpecialCH <- as.factor(data$SpecialCH)
data$SpecialMM <- as.factor(data$SpecialMM)
training_ratio <- 0.75 
set.seed(314)
train_indices <- createDataPartition(y = data$Purchase,
                                     times = 1,
                                     p = training_ratio,
                                     list = FALSE)
data_train <- data[train_indices, ]
data_test <- data[-train_indices, ]

b) Build a classification tree, determining the optimal complexity parameter via 10-fold cross validation.

  • Use values for the complexity parameter ranging between 0.001 and 0.1.
  • the selection criterion should be based on AUC
  • Use the one standard error rule to select the final model

Set train control to 10 fold CV and set the oneSE rule:

train_control <- trainControl(method = "cv",
                              number = 10,
                              classProbs = TRUE,
                              summaryFunction=twoClassSummary,
                              selectionFunction = "oneSE")

Train a simple tree model:

set.seed(314)
tree_model <- train(Purchase ~ .,
                    method = "rpart",
                    data = data_train,
                    tuneGrid = data.frame("cp" = seq(0.001, 0.1, 0.001)),
                    trControl = train_control,
                    metric = "ROC")

Get the properties of the best model:

results <- data.table(tree_model$results)



table0 <- data.table(results[cp == tree_model$bestTune$cp])

kable(table0, align = 'c', digits = 4)
cp ROC Sens Spec ROCSD SensSD SpecSD
0.019 0.8572 0.8469 0.7639 0.0482 0.0603 0.0856

We can see that the best model trained with cp = 0.19 and corresponding AUC/ROC which is 0.8572.

c) Plot the final model and interpret the result. How would you predict a new observation?

Plotting the best model:

rpart.plot(tree_model$finalModel)

Looking at the plot the first cut happens within the LoyalCH variable at the value of 0.48. Other cuts can be read from the plot too.

If we want to predict outcomes we should go through this plotted path above. Based on the variables of the new observations we can predict the outcome by going through a given path above. At the end of the path you will end up one of the bucket assigned with one of the predicted outcome. That will be your prediction for the new observation.

e.g.: you have an observation where the loyalCH = 0.4 then you go to the right part of the 1st cut. Then you got to left sine your variable is above 0.28. Then lets say your PriceDif variable is 0.4. You will end up in the CH bucket. Therefore this will be your prediction.

Now, draw an ROC Curve:

test_prediction_probs <- predict.train(tree_model, 
                                       newdata = data_test, 
                                       type = "prob")

is_CH <- ifelse(data_test$Purchase == "CH", 1 , 0)

rocr_prediction <- prediction(test_prediction_probs$CH, is_CH)

plot(performance(rocr_prediction, "tpr", "fpr"), colorize=TRUE)

Finally compute the AUC of the test set:

nrow(data_test)
## [1] 267
AUC <- performance(rocr_prediction, "auc")
print(AUC@y.values[[1]])
## [1] 0.89895

AUC is higher in the test set than in training set. But the difference is not high. It is most likely just a coincidence based on that the test set consists only 267 observations.

3) Variable importance profiles (4 points)

Use the Hitters dataset and predict log_salary just like we did it in class.

Load the data:

data <- data.table(Hitters)
data <- data[!is.na(Salary)]
data[, log_salary := log(Salary)]
data[, Salary := NULL]

a) train two random forest models: one with mtry = 2 and another with mtry = 10 (use the whole dataset and dont use cross-validation). Inspect variable importance profiles. What do you see in terms of how important the first few variables are relative to each other?

set.seed(314)
rf_model1 <- train(log_salary ~ .,
                  method = "rf",
                  data = data,
                  trControl = trainControl(method = "none"),
                  tuneGrid = data.frame(mtry = c(2)),
                  importance = T)

set.seed(314)
rf_model2 <- train(log_salary ~ .,
                  method = "rf",
                  data = data,
                  trControl = trainControl(method = "none"),
                  tuneGrid = data.frame(mtry = c(10)),
                  importance = T)
grid.arrange(textGrob("1st model (mtry = 2)"), textGrob("2nd model with (mtry = 10)"),
             plot(varImp(rf_model1)), plot(varImp(rf_model2)),
             ncol = 2,
             heights=unit(c(10,100), c("mm", "mm")))

b) One of them is more extreme in terms of how the most important and the next ones relate to each other. Give an intuitive explanation how mtry relates to relative importance of variables in random forest models.

In case of the 2nd model, where we used mtry = 10 the variable importance plot shows a not as smoother distribution as in the case of mtry = 2. There are not large drops regarding importance of the variable, but the next ones are always a little bit lower. In the mtry = 2 case the variables seems like grouped together and there are large drops after 4-5 variables.
I think, the underlying reason for this phenomenon is that the model can select to take the splits among 10 variables in the case of mtry = 10. Therefore, if some of our variables are very important their have more chance to be selected at the beginning of the trees building method and this will result of higher importance for them.
In the other case where we forced our model to build trees based on two variables (mtry = 2) we force our model to select among only just two variables, so it is inevitable to assign high importance two variables which are taking part of the models. (I dont know how to explain better this phenomenon, but maybe you get the intuition how I understand the methods)

c) In the same way, estimate two gbm models and set bag.fraction to 0.1 first and to 0.9 in the second. The tuneGrid should consist of the same values for the two models (a dataframe with one row):

  • n.trees = 500
  • interaction.depth = 5
  • shrinkage = 0.1
  • n.minobsinnode = 5

Compare variable importance plots for the two models. What is the meaning of bag.fraction? Based on this, why is one variable importance profile more extreme than the other?

gbm_grid <- expand.grid(n.trees = c(500), 
                        interaction.depth = c(5), 
                        shrinkage = c(0.1),
                        n.minobsinnode = c(5))

set.seed(314)
gbm_model1 <- train(log_salary ~ .,
                    method = "gbm",
                    data = data,
                    trControl = trainControl(method = "none"),
                    tuneGrid = gbm_grid,
                    verbose = FALSE,
                    bag.fraction = 0.1)

set.seed(314)
gbm_model2 <- train(log_salary ~ .,
                    method = "gbm",
                    data = data,
                    trControl = trainControl(method = "none"),
                    tuneGrid = gbm_grid,
                    verbose = FALSE,
                    bag.fraction = 0.9)

grid.arrange(textGrob("1st model (bf = 0.1)"), textGrob("2nd model (bf = 0.9)"),
             plot(varImp(gbm_model1)), plot(varImp(gbm_model2)),
             ncol = 2,
             heights=unit(c(10,100), c("mm", "mm")))

The fraction of the training set observations randomly selected to propose the next tree in the expansion. In this case, it adopts stochastic gradient boosting strategy.

If we set bag.fraction to 0.1 the next tree will be build on a much smaller sample then in the case of 0.9. This will result in that the model has not have time for a lots of round to train the model, and based on the small sample the chance that it will capture some noise in the data is much more likely then in the case of bag.fraction = 0.9. Based on the above mentioned information the variables importance plot will be something similar as we can see in the 1st plot if we use bag.fraction = 0.1 where the variable importance are not so diverse as in the 2nd plot where the value of bag.fraction is 0.9.
